name: Bishop Gang
text:
I purchased my Wren home while living in Massachusetts in early December of 2021. At that time, the Wren team set a schedule for the walkthroughs, home inspection, and new home presentation. The goal was to have everything buttoned up on January 8, 2020, in time for the January 11th closing.  The builder did not meet any of the promised dates.  I came down to Alabama the weekend of December 12, 2020, to do a house walkthrough. That inspection produced a long list of visual deficiencies that I provided to my realtor and the builder’s realtor. After that initial walkthrough, we had our home inspection and our blue tape to finalize the long list of repairs.  In short, 75% of the repairs did not happen until January 10th and the morning of the 11th.
Our closing was pushed back to allow the builder time to fix items that were identified in December.  The builder was not even aware of the remaining items until I showed up with my family on January 9th and pointed out the laundry list of issues remaining. In the end, we were left to accept a home with five official items remaining to be fixed. However, because we only had an hour between the final home presentation and closing, I felt pressured to accepted several other low craftsmanship items. The paint on the kitchen cabinets is cracking, an unsafe installation of an outside light switch, improper repair of the fireplace,  large scratch on the front door, residual mortar all over the bathroom floor and fireplace, sprinklers buried in the ground,  and the outside of the house was left filthy.
I give the construction team credit for getting a bunch of the issues fixed the day prior/to the closing. However, it should never come down to the last minute when they had a month lead time. In 2013, I purchased a new home back in Massachusetts, and the experience was ultimately the opposite of this purchase.  I had zero stress, and the process was a pleasure from start to finish. In contrast, my experience with Wren home was the most stressful financial transaction of my life. In the end, I needed a way to put all of the stress I experienced buying this house behind me so I can move forward. I pray this helps another family make the right decision when selecting a builder.  I can 100% relate to Corey’s experience, as I felt like reading my own story.  When the same information comes from two people who’ve never met, there might be some truth to the experience.

Update:
The Project Management team and the owner came out and went through the house. We came up with a list of repair work that would happen on a Friday and Monday. The cabinet company, painter, and fan contractor came out on Friday. The fan guy put weight on and was gone in 5 minutes without fixing the issue. The painter painted 1/4 of the side of my house the wrong color. Now I have a brand new house with multi color siding.  As far as I can see there is zero oversight on the contractors that are making the repairs.  More to follow.

Check you closest if you have kids. It's been 3 weeks since my closets started falling apart and they still haven't fixed it. The same thing happened to my neighbor and he said it took months of badgering them to get it fixed. Buyer beware, Wren Homes will fight and bully you every step of the way on repairs.

We were told all throughout the final stages of the build that everything was "on time" and then 6 days before close, they attempted to force us to move our walkthrough back because they weren't ready. At that time, we had already sold our other house, loaded our belongings on a moving truck, so we were essentially homeless and under threat of not closing on time because they didn't realize how far behind they were until the last possible minute. We decided we were coming to do a walkthrough anyways and realized they were not completing several things on time for us to close.

After closing, I have since found several items that Wren Home's quality control did not catch (cut HDMI cable, garage door opener not working, Carrier unit freezing over, mount in shower not attached properly, our blue tape touch ups were not finished, shoddy framing had to be corrected around our bathroom mirrors, and most of our hardware is still covered in paint) and continue to find things almost daily that are indicative of shoddy craftsmanship. At one point, I had put in several calls to try and get a status update on the warranty issues and was told that "everyone has been very busy" and that the VP who oversaw the last week of our construction "doesn't typically talk to buyers so you won't likely hear from him", indicating that once a purchase is complete, a customer is no longer a priority. I have been promised several call-backs and responses and have yet to receive a single one. When I call their personnel to try and reach someone...anyone, and express my frustration, I am the one that is called "rude".

We spent 100s of thousands of dollars on a house from Wren Homes and the experience we have received has been dismissive and neglectful. It is a sellers market and Wren Homes appears to be taking full advantage of that in their treatment of customers. My wife and I have collectively purchased 9 homes throughout our lives so I can speak from a level of experience that buying from Wren Homes has been the most painful buying experience we have ever had. We have experienced a laundry list of unprofessional and alarming acts from them so we would strongly caution other prospective home buyers to look elsewhere when choosing a homebuilder.

name: Karen Senn
text: Last year Medjet assisted my husband after a horrendous fall on some concrete steps in Vail, Colorado. The accident shattered his left hip and femur. The doctors said it was one of the worst fractures they had ever seen, with the bones in many pieces. He was rushed into surgery at Vail Hospital where the orthopedic surgeon stabilized the bones with two titanium rods. He was unable to travel via regular air flights. We were trying to figure out how we could get home to San Diego, since he was also unable to travel by car. I remembered that he was a Medjet member and contacted you. What your employees and organization accomplished was nothing short of miraculous.  After a 5 day hospital stay, all arrangements were promptly  made and coordinated between the Vail Hospital, our San Diego hospital, and your air transport. Your people put him on a gurney, drove to the Eagle Vail airport, loaded him onto the small jet, and flew smoothly to San Diego, unloaded him to a waiting ambulance and placed him into a waiting bed, all without causing excruciating pain which any movement exasperated. Your personnel, 2 pilots, one EMT, and one nurse could not have been more professional, kind and efficient. We will be eternally grateful for the quick response and ability to solve numerous problems which were encountered due to hospital bureaucracy and a blinding snowstorm.  My husband and I had been Medjet members for years, and thought we would never have to avail ourselves of your services, even though we travel extensively both at home and internationally.  Our future travel will be with peace of mind knowing that your company and personnel are always there to support us in a crisis.  Thank you for providing an invaluable service, it is worth every penny.
